@node "Tips" "Tips"
@prev "Tools"

@{u}@{b}Tips@{uu}@{ub}

                                 @{b}Tip #1@{ub}

Let's  say you want to, for some special reason, randomly show some pictures
which are placed in more than one directory.  This can be easily achieved by
editing the '.syspics' file - just add absolute paths for these pictures.


                                 @{b}Tip #2@{ub}

Pictures  will  be generally shown faster when they are unpacked ILBMs.  See
@{"UnpackILBM" link UnpackILBM} utility.


                                 @{b}Tip #3@{ub}

Fade-out  looks  best  when the picture and Workbench are displayed with the
same  monitor  driver.   Otherwise  the  monitor  will have to resync during
fading what would look ugly.  Use @{"ModeID" link Usage} and/or @{"Monitor" link Usage} options pair or
just save the picture in desired display mode.


                                 @{b}Tip #4@{ub}

Fade-out would also look ugly if you display smaller pictures than Workbench
screen and the BBlank option is turned on.


                                 @{b}Tip #5@{ub}

One  more  issue  about  fade-out...   If you don't want to waste any second
while  booting  (this is what SysPic is meant to) set ClosePic's STARTPRI to
lower  value,  so  some programs from 'WBStartup' will be loaded later while
SysPic is fading-out the picture.  In my 'WBStartup' drawer it looks like:

        ...
        ClosePic                -90
        SwazInfo                -100
        ToolsDaemon             -120
        AutoAssign              -127

Play  with  it  to  achieve  best  result  - Workbench screen should fade-in
exactly as the last program is loaded.


                                 @{b}Tip #6@{ub}

SysPic  changes  it's  current  dir  to the one in which picture (or script)
exists.   This  means  you  can  use  relative paths for 'Sound' or 'Module'
options.  E.g

SysPic Data:bootpics/pic1.ilbm SOUND /samples/yabadabadoo.8svx


                                 @{b}Tip #7@{ub}

If the contents of your static ram (e.g statram.device or static.device)
disappers after installing SysPic there are two solutions:
  - don't use 'NoFrag' option (but you lose the neat feature)
  - mount the ram device _before_ SysPic (recommended)
See @{"Bugs" link Bugs}.

                                 @{b}Tip #8@{ub}

Reverse typing is possible with fixed fonts, by using a negative 'typespace'
value. Let's say you use topaz.font/8:

TYPESPACE -16
TEXT "): !sgnirts eht esrever ot tegrof t'noD"

@endnode

